msItem.title: Moralia in Iob
msItem.incipit: 1r: uerba per syllabas percipit uisus autem noster in eo quo se dirigit

collation.p:
The manuscript comprises fourteen quires, mostly of eight leaves. There are quires missing after Quire 3 and Quire 9, and single leaves before ff. 1, 58, 69, 80 and 91 (doubtless removed for their initials).
Two medieval leaves (ff. i-ii)
Quire 18-1 (ff. 1-7: 1st leaf, before f. 1, missing)
Quire 28-2 (ff. 8-13: 4th and 5th leaves, after f. 10, missing)
Quires 3-78 (ff. 14-53)
Quire 88-1 (ff. 54-60: 5th leaf, after f. 57, missing)
Quires 9-108 (ff. 61-76)
Quire 118-1 (ff. 77-83: 4th leaf, after f. 79, missing)
Quire 128-1 (ff. 84-90: 8th leaf, after f. 90, missing)
Quire 138 (ff. 91-98)
Quire 144-1 (ff. 99-101: 3rd leaf, after f. 100, missing)
18-1 (1 missing) 28-2 (4, 5 missing) 3-78 88-1 (5 missing) 9-108 118-1 (4 missing) 128-1 (8 missing) 134-1 (3 missing)

supportDesc.condition: Folio 69 has suffered liquid damage. All but one of the major initials in the text have been excised.

layout.seg: Ruled in leadpoint. Two columns. 39-40 lines to the page. Written above top line.
Paratext: running heads written on a specially ruled line. Chapter numbers added in the margins by a much later hand.

handNote.p: Protogothic. Parker McLachlan's Scribe A, the first scribe of Cambridge, Pembroke College, MS 12.

decoNote.p: Zoomorphic initial I in the form of a dragon, in red, green, violet and gold, with heading in capitals in the same colours (f. 36r).
Two-line initials in red, green, violet and blue, sometimes with a little foliage ornament.

binding.p: Original, repaired and rebacked under the old spine by Douglas Cockerell Cockerell, Douglas and Son in 1972: tawed skin over flush, square-edged oak boards; sewn on three bands, not raised on the flat spine; tabs at each end, heavily repaired; lined with textile of uncertain colour. Marks of chain-staples at head and foot of the front cover. Formerly two straps from recesses in the front board to pins at the rear. Formerly a rectangular label near the top of the rear cover: six iron nails remain.

Folios i-ii and 101 are former pastedowns. Folios i-ii were originally pasted together and to the front board. Folio i recto has a few lines of faint writing, including one in Hebrew. On f. ii verso, titles of s. xii (Tertia Pars) and later, and a circular diagram in ink (partially obscured by the College bookplate).

history.origin:
2nd quarter of the 12th century. England, Bury St Edmunds.
The manuscript was made and kept at the Abbey of Bury St Edmunds Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds .
CBMLC 4, B13.168
history.acquisition: Given to Pembroke College, Cambridge Pembroke College in 1599 by William Smart (d. 1599) Smart, William, portreeve of Ipswich, -1599 . The College bookplate is pasted onto f. ii verso. James, Ecloga, 23 or 207

availability.p: Researchers should note that Pembroke College's western European medieval manuscripts are housed at Cambridge University Library (CUL). Scholars who wish to consult Pembroke College manuscripts should contact the Manuscripts Reading Room at CUL to arrange their visit; all CUL admissions procedures will apply. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library. For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
